---
title: "The Rise and Fall of Bitcoin"
author: "Benjamin Wallace"
domain: "wired.com"
url: "https://www.wired.com/2011/11/mf-bitcoin/"
pubDate: 2011-07-23
takeaway: "A seminal, early narrative piece exploring the cypherpunk origins, decentralized design, and wild early market bubbles of Bitcoin."
---

Reading Benjamin Wallace's 2011 piece on Bitcoin feels like opening a time capsule from a completely different tech era. Written back when Bitcoin was still largely a playground for cypherpunks, geeks, and early internet idealists, the article perfectly captures the raw, anarchic energy of its origins. As an engineer, looking back at this early period reminds me of the beautiful simplicity of the original whitepaper—a elegant, trustless consensus protocol designed to solve double-spending without a central authority, before it was buried under layers of financial speculation and institutional hype.

For a startup founder, the early history of Bitcoin is a masterclass in how community and narrative can drive the adoption of a highly abstract technology. What started as an obscure mailing list project mutated into a global movement because it addressed a deep, systemic distrust in centralized financial institutions following the 2008 crash. It's a powerful reminder that the most disruptive technologies rarely succeed purely on technical merits; they win because they align with a powerful cultural or political undercurrent at a specific moment in time.

### What stuck with me

* **Elegant decentralized design**: The breakthrough of solving the double-spending problem without a central intermediary remains one of the most elegant distributed systems achievements in computing history.
* **Narrative-driven adoption**: Bitcoin’s initial momentum was powered as much by ideological opposition to central banking as it was by its cryptographic capabilities.
* **Vulnerability of early markets**: The volatile boom-and-bust cycles of early crypto demonstrated how fragile decentralized networks are before they establish deep liquidity and institutional infrastructure.
